### Part 2: Fix Map Drag Conflict

**Strategy:** Move drag listeners from SortableWidget wrapper to Widget header only.

**Option A: Modify SortableWidget to Accept Drag Handle (Recommended)**
- Pass drag listeners as prop to Widget component
- Widget applies listeners ONLY to header
- Map remains interactive

**Option B: Use DragHandle Pattern**
- Create separate drag handle component
- Only that handle triggers drag
- More explicit control

**I recommend Option A for cleaner implementation.**

**File:** `src/components/SortableWidget.tsx`
```tsx
// BEFORE (Lines 32-42):
<div
  ref={setNodeRef}
  style={style}
  className={`sortable-widget ${className}`}
  {...attributes}
  {...listeners}  // ← Applied to entire widget (BAD)
>
  {children}
</div>

// AFTER:
<div
  ref={setNodeRef}
  style={style}
  className={`sortable-widget ${className}`}
  {...attributes}
  // Listeners removed from wrapper - will be passed to children
>
  {React.cloneElement(children as React.ReactElement, {
    dragListeners: listeners, // Pass listeners to child
  })}
</div>
```

**File:** `src/components/Widget.tsx`
```tsx
// Add dragListeners prop to WidgetProps type
export const Widget: React.FC<WidgetProps> = ({
  id,
  title,
  category,
  className = '',
  children,
  headerAccessory,
  draggable = true,
  dragListeners, // NEW: Drag listeners from SortableWidget
}) => {
  return (
    <div ...>
      {/* Widget Header - Apply drag listeners HERE only */}
      <div
        className="px-4 py-3 border-b ... cursor-grab active:cursor-grabbing"
        {...dragListeners}  // ← Drag only from header
      >
        {/* Header content */}
      </div>

      {/* Widget Content - NO drag listeners */}
      <div className="p-4 overflow-auto">
        {children}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};
```

**Result:**
- ✅ Map can be panned without triggering widget drag
- ✅ Widget still draggable from header
- ✅ Better UX

